<DOC><DOCNO> AP880405-0215 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 2137EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-US-JapanExports     04-05 0210</FIRST><SECOND>AM-US-Japan Exports,210</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. Welcomes Japanese Crackdown On Strategic Arms Sales</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Commerce Department on Tuesday praisedJapan's ``new energy and dedication'' in tightening controls onsales of strategic exports to communist countries.   Paul Freedenberg, undersecretary of commerce for exportadministration, said Tokyo's reported crackdown on two Japanesefirms accused of violating export regulations in the sale ofelectronic measuring equipment to China ``demonstrates Japan'sserious regard for protecting sensitive technology.''   ``We are beginning to see actions that demonstrate Japan'scommitment to a strong and effective export control regime, acommitment that has recently been reinforced with increased fundsand stronger export control laws,'' Freedenberg said in a statement.   He added that the latest actions underscore ``the new energy anddedication of the Japanese government in administering andenforcing multilateral export control rules.''   He cited the Japanese government's announcement Monday that itwas investigating alleged export violations by Kyokuto Shokai Co.Ltd. and Shinseki Koeki Co. Ltd.   The Japanese Ministry of International Trade and Industry saidthe companies' sales to China occurred in 1985-86, prior to thetightening of trade laws brought about by the disclosure thatToshiba Machine Corp. had illegally exported machinery used in theproduction of silent submarine propellors to the Soviet Union.</TEXT></DOC>